Eltek Smartpack2 Master Controller — Installation & User Guide, -48 V DC telecom power system (excerpt). Vendor: Eltek. Controller for Flatpack2 rectifier shelves at cell sites; alarm limits, voltage sensing, supervision module.

## DC undervoltage alarm limit — evaluated on the controller sense channel

The DC undervoltage alarms are controller-configured limits (minor around -47.0 V, major around -45.0 V, each debounced) held in the controller's alarm-limit table and evaluated against the bus voltage on the controller's voltage-sense input. In normal operation an undervoltage alarm means the bus really has fallen to the limit — typically because rectifier capacity was lost (a module fault) and the plant is running down onto its batteries. That is the default interpretation, and it is confirmed by coherent telemetry: a low reported bus together with a rectifier module fault and battery discharge. Because the limit is evaluated on the sense channel, there is one specific exception: when an independent field measurement at the bar contradicts the reading — the bus measured at normal float while the alarm is active — the low value is a sense-channel artifact rather than a real sag. That reinterpretation requires the contradicting measurement; without it, an undervoltage alarm is treated as a real low bus. The upper float/overvoltage limit (e.g. 57.00 V) is likewise evaluated on the same channel.

## Voltage sensing input and the supervision module

The Smartpack2 senses bus voltage through the supervision module's voltage-sense leads at the DC distribution bar, digitises it, and publishes it to the controller and the NOC; the rectifiers regulate the bus independently of this sensing. A supervision-module fault — ADC drift, a degraded reference, or a corroded/loose sense lead — can therefore make the controller report a bus voltage that differs from the true value at the bar, characteristically reading low. This possibility is confirmed, not assumed: it is established only by comparing the controller's reported voltage against an independent DMM measurement at the bar. When the two agree, the reported voltage is trustworthy and a low reading is a real low bus (a rectifier/plant fault); when the DMM reads normal float while the controller reports low, the supervision module is the fault.

## Identifying a failed supervision module

The defining indicator of a supervision/sensing fault is a contradiction with a field measurement: the controller reports undervoltage but the bus measured at the bar with a DMM is normal float (for example -53.9 V). Supporting indicators, all secondary to that measurement: the reported voltage does not track the DMM as load changes; no battery-discharge current; mains present; no rectifier drawing the plant down. In the absence of a contradicting field measurement, do not attribute an undervoltage to the supervision module — coherent telemetry (a low bus together with a rectifier module fault) indicates a real plant fault, and a dark rectifier module LED with a genuinely low measured bus is a real undervoltage, not a sensing artifact. A failed rectifier module can coexist with a sensing fault, but which is which is resolved by the field measurement, not by the alarm.

## Replacing the supervision module (SP2-MU)

Once a contradicting field measurement has confirmed the supervision module as the fault, replace it. The supervision/sensing module (order code SP2-MU) is field-replaceable and the replacement is a monitoring operation: the DC output stays up and the site is not interrupted, because the rectifiers hold the bus independently of the controller's sensing. Procedure: note the reported vs measured bus voltage; swap the SP2-MU supervision module; allow the controller to re-enumerate; then verify that the controller's newly reported bus voltage tracks a calibrated DMM reading at the bar within tolerance before trusting the channel for alarming again. Restore the alarm-limit table to the configured minor/major undervoltage limits. Only after this verification should the monitoring point drive NOC dispatch decisions.

## LVD and alarm-limit table reference

The controller also holds the low-voltage-disconnect (LVD) settings and battery-alarm limits in the same configured table; alarmLVD1open asserts when the sensed bus reaches the LVD threshold. As with undervoltage, every limit is evaluated against the supervision-module sense channel, so these indications are real by default and are trusted unless a direct field measurement at the bar contradicts them. Verify the sense channel against a DMM before attributing any voltage-derived alarm to the sensing path rather than the plant.
